          <div class="col-xs-offset-1 col-xs-10 col-xs-offset-1"> <button type="button" class="btn btn-info" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#demo29">What is the relationship between alcohol and sexual assault?</button>
               	  <div></br></div>
				  <div id="demo29" class="collapse">
				      <div>
				      	  <p>Most sexual assaults on a college campus are non-stranger assaults, meaning that the individuals involved knew each other. Alcohol is a factor in many of these non-stranger sexual assaults as every year more than 70,000 college students ages 18-24 are victims of sexual assault in which alcohol use was involved.</p><br>
				          <p>In some cases people drink in the context of wanting to “hook-up” with someone. In cases such as these individuals who have been drinking may be more likely to act on a belief that it is okay to engage in sexual activity without getting the other person’s consent or their alcohol use may make it feel easier for them to ignore the need to get consent. Drinking may also reduce an individual’s ability to process and react to the other person’s behavioral cues indicating that they do not want to engage in sexual activity. Intoxication is not an excuse for sexual assault and an intoxicated person can be held responsible for their actions.</p><br>
				          <p>Some people who have committed sexual assault might have encouraged their victims to drink large amounts of alcohol or might have intentionally sought out those who were already drunk. Every year more than 100,000 students report having been too intoxicated to know if they consented to having sex. Remember, <strong>a person who is intoxicated cannot legally provide consent for sexual activity.</strong></p><br>
