            <h1 class="page-header col-xs-offset-4 col-xs-4 col-xs-offset-4">Tips Bank</h1>
            <div class="col-xs-offset-1 col-xs-10 col-xs-offset-1"><div class="panel panel-default">
  <div class="panel-heading">Risk reduction tips: Avoiding the Not-So-Good Things about Drinking</div>
  <div class="panel-body">
   <p>
   1.	A large glass of wine can contain over 1.5 standard drinks of alcohol. Think about how that adds up over a night if you’re drinking more than one, and perhaps go for a smaller glass for a change.<br><br>

2.	Think about how much you’re going to drink before you go on a night out. One way of making sure you don’t go over this is to take only enough money to buy the drinks you want (and a bit more to get you home safely).<br><br> 

3.	Eat a good meal before you start drinking, or enjoy some snacks while you drink. This helps to slow down the effect of alcohol on your body.<br><br>

4.	Drink water regularly whilst you’re out drinking as it will help you cut down the number of standard drinks you consume and avoid a hangover the next day and also when you get home to keep hydrated.<br><br> 

5.	The guidelines are lower than you might think – women should not regularly drink more than 1 standard drink per day and men 2. <br><br>

6.	Aim to have at least 2 alcohol-free days every week to give your body a break.<br><br>

7.	The strength of drinks varies dramatically depending on what you’re drinking. So make sure you know how many units are in your drink, and keep tabs on your intake. A cocktail can contain as many as 1.5 standard drinks, while a 750ml bottle of table wine (12% vol) totals 5 standard drinks<br><br> 

8.	Use a standard drinks measure cup to keep track of how much you’re pouring at home. <br><br>

9.	Try keeping a drinking diary, noting how much you drank and where and you’ll get a better idea of your alcohol intake.<br><br> 

10.	Try to avoid multi-buy offers. Their prices might tempt you, but so will the big quantities of alcohol you’ll have in the cupboard.<br><br> 

11.	Drink familiar drinks in familiar places with familiar people<br><br>

12.	Don’t drink anything that you don’t know<br><br>

13.	Use the buddy system when drinking <br><br>

14.	Avoid drinking games<br><br>

15.	No drinking before driving<br><br>

16.	Plan to sleep over if you drove (put your keys away)<br><br>

17.	Drinking games may seem fun at the time but often lead to rapid overdrinking that in effect increases risks of not-so-good consequences of drinking<br><br>

18.	Drinking games are exciting and have risk of the competition, it is easy to lose track of how much is drunk.<br><br>

19.	Goal of the game, to drink a lot in a short amount of time, also means that blood alcohol level will be rapidly on the rise, placing participants at risk for blackouts, embarrassing behavior while in blackouts, and risk of injury due to poor coordination and judgment (see alcohol myopia).<br><br> 

20.	Drinking unknown amounts or types of alcohol prevents observing when you have had enough. Knowing exactly what you are putting into your body is a good thing!<br><br>

21.	use the buddy system when drinking, which simply means taking along a friend or friends to drinking events.<br><br>

22.	There is strength in numbers, and having a friend watching your back while you are watching theirs increases the likelihood of a good time.<br><br> 

23.	The best strategy is not to drive to drinking events, and not to ride with others who have been drinking.<br><br>

24.	If you do drive to a party in which you plan to drink, make plans to spend the night and sleep off the effects of alcohol.<br><br>
25.	Make sure that your keys are safe so you will not be tempted to drive after you have been drinking (and after alcohol myopia sets in).<br><br>

26.	Well-known strategies, the ideas of arranging rides and using designated drivers.<br><br>

27.	Ask drivers if they drank alcohol.<br><br>

28.	Carry extra money to parties and drinking venues if a taxi is needed.<br><br>

29.	Avoiding driving after drinking, which is perhaps the most risky not-so-good thing about drinking.<br><br>

30.	Taking some to think about and plan drinking often leads to positive drinking experiences because planning tends to reduce the risk of over drinking.<br><br> 

31.	 Drinking too much, including binge drinking, cost $746 per person, or $1.90 a drink, in the US in 2006. These costs include health care expenses, crime, and lost productivity.<br><br>


32.	Drinking too much contributes to over 54 different injuries and diseases, including car crashes, violence, and sexually-transmitted diseases.<br><br>

33.	The chance of getting sick and dying from alcohol problems increases significantly for those who binge drink more often and drink more when they do.<br><br>

34.	A few ways to manage stress are to get enough sleep , avoid drugs and alcohol, connect socially and also take time for yourself.<br><br>

35.	Follow an eating plan with portions from the basic food groups. Also be aware that beverages may be adding extra calories.<br><br>

36.	Be creative about ways to get in exercise like walking across campus instead of driving, taking the stairs instead of the elevator, and working out with a friend, group or joining an intramural sports team.<br><br>

37.	The best thing you can do is to drink plenty of water, eat a potassium rich snack like a banana and go for a stroll to get some fresh air.<br><br>

38.	Strong, healthy nails rely on a balanced intake of nutrients and plenty of water. Brittle nails could be one sign you’re drinking more than you think.<br><br>

39.	 Your hair also relies on your body being hydrated. Regular drinking can leave you with dry and brittle hair. Excessive drinking depletes iron and can cause hair loss.<br><br>

40.	A few too many drinks before bedtime and you might think you’re getting off to sleep quickly, but an excess of alcohol means you can go straight into deep sleep missing out the usual first stage of rapid eye movement (REM) sleep. Instead of having typically 6-7 cycles of REM sleep you’ll only have 1-2 meaning you’ll wake up feeling tired.<br><br>

41.	Drinking also causes heartburn and because it relaxes the muscles in your body including the throat, it increases your likelihood of snoring. For a great night’s sleep, make that nightcap a glass of water.<br><br>

42.	Alcohol can do more than leave you struggling to remember the events of the night before. Over time, heavy drinking can lead to memory loss problems – in particular, a Vitamin B1 deficiency causes Wernicke-Korsakoff's Syndrome – a dementia-like illness.<br><br>

43.	People who drink too much are often overweight - and as a result, can go on to develop diabetes. Although the condition is manageable, diabetes can reduce your lifespan and require a careful diet as well as daily medication or insulin injections.<br><br>

44.	Drinking in moderation can help to lower your risk of heart attack and stroke.<br><br>
45.	 For both men and women, too much alcohol lowers your fertility. As few as five drinks a week reduces a woman's chance of becoming pregnant and in men regularly drinking too much can lower sperm count.<br><br>

46.	  Plan ahead and carry a condom with you, it could decrease your risk of getting a sexually transmitted disease, or having an unwanted pregnancy.<br><br>

47.	Don’t accept drinks from strangers and watch your drink at all times.<br><br>

48.	If you’re being provoked by someone who has been drinking, the best advice is to walk away.<br><br>

49.	 People who fall asleep outside after drinking alcohol are at risk of hypothermia and even death. Even if you’re still awake, if it’s a cold night and you’re not dressed for the weather, there’s still a risk of hypothermia.<br><br>

50.	 Finding a taxi can be difficult late at night, so you might want to book one in advance. And make sure you keep some money back so you can pay for it. If you're walking, walk with someone you know and trust.<br><br>

51.	 If you have to walk alone, stick to well-lit and well-used routes and keep your mobile handy. Let someone know what you're doing if you can and call them when you get home.<br><br>

52.	 Try to find ways to get out and have fun that don't always involve alcohol.<br><br>

53.	Avoid drinking in rounds and don't be pushed into drinking more than you'd like to.<br><br>

54.	If you're feeling the pressure to drink when you're out, there are lots of tricks you can use such as alternating 'or spacing' alcohol with soft drinks or water, or ordering a small glass of wine rather than a large one to stop you from overdoing it.<br><br>

55.	Eat a good meal before you start drinking, or enjoy some snacks while you drink. This helps to slow down the effect of alcohol on your body.<br><br>

56.	Aim to have at least 2 alcohol-free days every week to give your body a break.<br><br>

57.	Try keeping a drinking diary, noting how much you drank and where and you’ll get a better idea of your alcohol intake.<br><br>

58.	Try to avoid multi-buy offers. Their prices might tempt you, but so will the big quantities of alcohol you’ll have in the cupboard.<br><br>
   
